ğŸ“¦ Component Roles
ğŸ§  What Is a Server?
A server is a computer designed to receive requests from clients (like browsers) and respond with dataâ€”like web pages, files, or JSON APIs. In this case, it's the one-stop shop that does everything.

ğŸŒ Domain Name Role
The domain name (foobar.com) is a readable alias for an IP address. Itâ€™s easier for users to remember.

ğŸ“‡ DNS Record: www
www is a subdomain.

The record type is an A record.

It maps www.foobar.com to the IP 8.8.8.8.

ğŸ”¥ Web Server (Nginx)
Listens for HTTP(S) requests on port 80/443.

Delivers static files like images, CSS, JS.

Acts as a reverse proxy, forwarding dynamic requests to the application server.

âš™ï¸ Application Server (e.g. PHP-FPM)
Processes business logic.

Executes the application code (like index.php).

Interfaces with the database to fetch/store data.

ğŸ’¾ Database (MySQL)
Stores all persistent data: user accounts, blog posts, products, etc.

The application queries it using SQL.

ğŸ§µ Communication Protocol
Communication between the user's browser and the web server uses HTTP or HTTPS, over TCP/IP.

âš ï¸ Weaknesses of This Setup
1. SPOF (Single Point of Failure)
One server = one place to crash. If it dies, your entire website goes offline.

2. Maintenance Downtime
If you need to update the app, restart Nginx, or apply security patches, you must stop or restart the server. Boomâ€”temporary downtime.

3. No Scalability
One server handles all requests. If traffic spikes (say, a viral post or product launch), it will choke and possibly crash.

ğŸ§  Summary
This setup is simple and cheapâ€”perfect for prototypes, portfolios, or small apps. But if the site grows, youâ€™ll quickly need:

Load balancers

Separate DB server

App replication

Cloud scaling
